anistan, Iraq, and Somalia|title=Small Arms Survey 2012: Moving Targets|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2012|author=Small Arms Survey|page=321|isbn= 978-0-521-19714-4|author-link=Small Arms Survey}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ireland}}:{{sfn|BICC|p=4}} 123 used by the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Irish Defence Forces]] during [[The Emergency (Ireland)|the Emergency]].\n*{{flag|Israel}}:<ref name=Eilam/>\n*{{flag|Italy}}: Captured examples pressed into use by the Italian Army prior to [[Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces|September 8, 1943]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digilander.libero.it/lacorsainfinita/guerra2/42/birelgobi2.htm |title=Bir El Gobi: la battaglia |publisher=Digilander.libero.it |date= |accessdate=2011-12-25}}</ref> Also supplied to [[Italian resistance movement|partisans]] and to the [[Italian Co-belligerent Army]].<ref>Romain Rainero, Antonello Biagini, ''L'Italia in guerra: Il 6\u00b0 anno, 1945'' published by Commissione italiana di storia militare, 1996.{{page needed|date=December 2011}}</ref> After the war, it was mostly issued to [[Italian Air Force]] troopers<ref>As pictured in the book ''Ho vestito in azzurro'' by Nicola Malizia, IBN 2005. {{page needed|date=December 2011}}</ref> and the [[Carabinieri]].<ref>As mentioned in a notorious reportage on the death of outlaw [[Salvatore Giuliano]]:http://www.ilcassetto.it/notizia.php?tid=148</ref>\n*{{flag|Japan}}: Were used in some quantities by the [[Japanese Maritime Self-Defense Force]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jieitaisaiyou.web.fc2.com/gun.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306090423/http://jieitaisaiyou.web.fc2.com/gun.html|archive-date=6 March 2017|script-title=ja:\u81ea\u885b\u968a\u306e\u9283\u5668\u5404\u7a2e|language=ja|website=jieitaisaiyou.web.fc2.com}}{{unreliable source?|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Jordan}}<ref name=\"Arabs\">{{cite book|title=Arab Armies of the Middle East Wars 1948\u201373|series=Men-at-Arms 128|first=John |last=Laffin|date=15 Jun 1982|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=9780850454512|page=32}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Republic of Korea}}: Limited received U.S government used during the [[Korean War]] and [[Vietnam War]]. After the Vietnam War all Thompson SMGs were scrapped.\n*{{flag|Kingdom of Laos}}: Limited received by U.S government and used during the First Indochina War and Vietnam War.<ref>{{cite book|title=The War in Laos 1960\u201375|series=Men-at-Arms 217|first=Kenneth |last=Conboy|date=23 Nov 1989 |publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=9780850459388|page=15}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Luxembourg}}: M1A1 in service 1952-1967, replaced by [[Uzi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mnhm.lu/pageshtml/virtualmuseumtour.php |title=Grand-Duchy Of Luxembourg |publisher=Mnhm.lu |date= |accessdate=2011-12-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126105021/http://www.mnhm.lu/pageshtml/virtualmuseumtour.php |archivedate=2011-01-26 |df= }}</ref>\n*{{flag|Malaysia}}<ref name= 'bicc 3'/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*{{flag|The Netherlands}}: In early World War II, at least 3,680 Thompsons acquired through [[Lend-Lease]]<ref name=\"Frank Iannamico 1928\"/>\n*{{flag|New Zealand}}: M1928 and M1928A1<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Zealand Expeditionary Force in World War II|series=Men-at-Arms 486|first1=Wayne|last1=Stack|first2=Barry|last2=O\u2019Sullivan|date=20 Mar 2013|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=9781780961118|page=46}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Nicaragua|1908}}:{{sfn|Pegler|2010|p=56}} The [[National Guard (Nicaragua)|Nicaraguan National Guard]] received M1928A1s and some were captured by [[Augusto C\u00e9sar Sandino|Sandino]]'s rebels.<ref name=\"Banana\">{{cite book|title=Latin American Wars 1900\u20131941: \"Banana Wars,\" Border Wars & Revolutions|series=Men-at-Arms 519|publisher=Osprey Publishing|first= Philip |last=Jowett|date= 28 Jun 2018|isbn=9781472826282 |pages=44\u201345|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=8LJeDwAAQBAJ}}</ref>\n*{{flag|North Korea}}: Chinese-made Thompsons used by the Korean People's Army in the Korean War.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanwaronline.com/history/Enemy%20Weapons/Frames/39.htm|title=11mm Submachine Gun (China)}}</ref>\n*{{flag|North Vietnam}}: Unlicensed copies.<ref name=\"History\"/> Used by [[Viet Minh]] in the [[First Indochina War]].<ref name=\"Indochina\">{{cite book|title=The French Indochina War 1946\u201354|series=Men-at-Arms 322|first= Martin |last=Windrow|isbn=9781855327894 |date=15 Nov 1998|page=24|publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]]|ref=harv}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Pakistan}}: Used by the Pakistani army during the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]]\n*{{flag|Paraguay}}: possibly<ref name ='Chaco'>{{cite book|author=Alejandro de Quesada|title=The Chaco War 1932\u201335: South America's greatest modern conflict|url=https://books.google.fr/books/about/The_Chaco_War_1932_35.html?id=dTm3CwAAQBAJ|date=20 November 2011|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84908-901-2|page=24}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Philippines}}<ref name= 'bicc 3'/>\n*{{flag|Poland}}: Used by the [[Polish Armed Forces in the West]] during WWII<ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Army 1939\u201345|series= Men-at-Arms 117 |first=Steven J.|last=Zaloga|date=1982|isbn=9780850454178|publisher=Osprey Publishing|pages=22, 38}}</ref> and by resistance fighters during the [[Warsaw Uprising]] (from supply drops)\n*{{flag|Portugal}}: Small number bought for police use, designated m/1928<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revistamilitar.pt/modules/articles/article.php?id=528 |title=:: Revista Militar ::-Revistas \u2013 As Ind\u00fastrias Militares e As Armas de Fogo |publisher=Revistamilitar.pt |date=2010-05-28 |accessdate=2011-12-25 |language=Portuguese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327041640/http://www.revistamilitar.pt/modules/articles/article.php?id=528 |archivedate=2012-03-27 |df= }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Somalia}}<ref>{{cite news|title=La fusillade de Loyada : Quelle balle a tu\u00e9 ?|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/02/12/quelle-balle-a-tue_2958304_1819218.html|date=12 February 1976|newspaper=[[Le Monde]]|page=7|issue=9660|language=fr}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Union of South Africa}}\n*{{flag|South Vietnam}}<ref name=\"bishop1998\"/>\n*{{flag|Soviet Union}}<ref name=\"TG\">{{cite web|url=http://world.guns.ru/smg/smg29-e.htm|title=Thompson M1921 M1928 M1 and M1A1 submachine gun / \"Tommy Gun\" (USA)|accessdate=2009-09-22|publisher=World Guns|author=Maxim Popenker}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Sweden}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gotavapen.se/gota/artiklar/kpist/swede_45.htm|title=Submachine guns of Sweden|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Turkey}}: Used between 1950s\u20131970s, saw action in [[Korean War]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militaryphotos.net/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=165101&d=1321467248|title=Military Photos|work=militaryphotos.net}}</ref> and [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|1974 Cyprus War]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turkboard.com/fotograflarla-kibris-baris-harekati-18-vt174307.html|title=Foto\u011fraflarla K\u0131br\u0131s Bar\u0131\u015f Harekat\u0131 +18|work=turkboard.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulusalkanal.com.tr/images/album/konuksever18.jpg |title=Photo |website=www.ulusalkanal.com.tr |format=JPG |access-date=2019-07-13}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ukraine}}: observed, unknown user<ref name= 'bicc 3'/>\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}. First issued to the [[GHQ Liaison Regiment|GHQ Liaison Unit]] ('Phantom') in February 1940, in advance of main War Office contracts.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Fighting Nazi Occupation: British Resistance 1939 \u2013 1945|last = Atkin|first = Malcolm|publisher = Pen and Sword|year = 2015|isbn = 978-1-47383-377-7|location = |page = 80}}</ref>\n*{{flag|United States|1912}}: Employed by the [[United States Marine Corps]]<ref name=\"Fitz2487\"/> and by the [[United States Army]] 1938,<ref name=\"miller2001\">Miller, David (2001). ''The Illustrated Directory of 20th Century Guns''. Salamander Books Ltd. {{ISBN|1-84065-245-4}}. {{page needed|date=December 2011}}</ref> including [[paratroops]] in World War II.\n*{{flag|Vietnam}} Used by Vi\u1ec7t Minh and [[Viet Cong]] during Vietnam War.\n*{{flag|Venezuela|1930}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fav-club.com/legendarios/|title=Legendarios|accessdate=2017-02-24|publisher=FAV-Club|date=2013-12-18}}</ref>\n*{{flag|West Germany}}:<ref name= 'bicc 3'/> Used post [[World War II]]; received from the U.S government.\n*{{flag|Yugoslavia}}<ref name=\"Yugoslav Army\"/>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Non-state groups===\n*American organized crime syndicates, such as the [[Chicago Outfit]] and [[American Mafia]].\n*The [[Provisional IRA]] and [[Official IRA]] used the 1921 variant, mainly during the early 1960s to 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://libraryautomation.com/nymas/irishcivilwar.html|title=The Irish Civil War, 1922\u20131923|accessdate=2009-09-22|author=Paul V. Walsh}}</ref><ref name=\"O'Brien1993\">{{cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Brendan|title=The Long War: The IRA and Sinn F\u00e9in, 1985 to Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dy9WENSLHyQC&pg=PA279|year=1993|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0319-1|pages=279\u2013}}</ref>\n*Formerly used by the Viet Cong with clones made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tactical-life.com/firearms/viet-cong-weaponry-14-vietnam-war/#ms16-viet-3|title=Viet Cong Weaponry: 14 Small Arms From the Vietnam War|date=22 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[The Angry Brigade]]<ref name=\"Terrorists\">{{cite book|page=101|title=The Terrorists: Their Weapons, Leaders, and Tactics|author1=Christopher Dobson |author2=Ronald Payne|date=1982|publisher=Facts on File}}</ref>\n* [[26th of July Movement]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of U.S. Army weapons by supply catalog designation]] SNL A-32\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*Albert, David and Sig, Mike. (2005). ''Thompson Manuals, Catalogs, and Other Paper Items''. Self Published.\n*Bannan, James F. and Hill, Tracie L. (1989). ''Notes On Auto-Ordnance''. South West Publishing Co.\n* {{cite boo