chnical Publishing Company.\n*{{cite book |last= Yenne |first= Bill |year= 2009 |title= Tommy Gun: How General Thompson's Submachine Gun Wrote History |id= (340 pages; contains black-and-white photographs and illustrations) |publisher= St. Martin's Press |place= New York |isbn= 978-0-312-38326-8 |ref= {{harvid|Yenne|2009}} |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312383268 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|M1 Thompson}}\n*[http://www.auto-ordnance.com/ Auto Ordnance]\n*[http://www.machinegunboards.com/forums/index.php?showforum=3 Thompson Submachine Gun Discussion Forum]\n*[http://www.nfatoys.com/tsmg/ The Unofficial Tommy Gun Home Page]\n*[http://TheTCA.net/ The Official Thompson Collectors Association Page]\n*{{YouTube| bcBKnn8mGc0 | \"Thompson Submachine Gun: Principles of Operation 1943\" }}\n\n{{BritishEmpireWeapons}}\n{{WWIIUSInfWeaponsNav}}\n{{WWIIChineseInfantryWeapons}}\n{{Soviet infantry weapons of World War II}}\n{{WW2 Brit Comm infantry guns}}\n\n[[Category:.45 ACP submachine guns]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1919]]\n[[Category:Police weapons]]\n[[Category:Savage Arms]]\n[[Category:Submachine guns of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Army equipment]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps equipment]]\n[[Category:Weapons of the Philippine Army]]\n[[Category:World War II firearms of the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of Australia]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of China]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of France]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of Greece]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War II military equipment of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:World War II military equipment of Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:World War II submachine guns]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "disambig no longer exists", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thompson_submachine_gun"}
{"title_page": "Thomas FitzWilliam, 1st Viscount FitzWilliam", "text_new": "'''Thomas FitzWilliam, 1st Viscount Fitzwilliam''' (1581\u20131650) was an Irish nobleman of the Stuart age. He was born to wealth and privilege, and acquired a peerage, but due to his loyalty to the English  Crown he suffered  considerable hardship  during the [[English Civil War]], and died in poverty.\n\n==Background==\nHe was born in [[Dublin]], probably at [[Merrion Castle]], eldest of the five  sons  of Sir Richard FitzWiliam, Constable of [[Wicklow]], and Jane Preston, daughter of Christopher Preston, 4th [[Viscount Gormanston]].<ref>Ball, F. Elrington  ''History of Dublin'' Alexander Thom and Co. Dublin 1902-1920 Vol.2  p.11</ref> The FitzWilliam family are recorded   in Dublin from about 1210, and by the time of Thomas's  birth they  were among the wealthiest and most influential families in [[the Pale]].\n\n==Early career==\nThomas was only fourteen when his father died.  As a young man he spent some time in [[London]] studying law at [[Gray's Inn]].  He  was [[knighted]] in 1605, the year of his marriage.\n\nIn 1608 he narrowly avoided being caught up  in the rebellion of Sir [[Cahir O'Doherty]], having stood [[surety]]  for the good behaviour of O'Doherty, who had married Thomas's  aunt Mary Preston.<ref>Ball, p.12</ref> A messenger arrived at Merrion Castle ordering FitzWilliam to produce the person of O'Doherty; fortunately FitzWilliam was not at home.  \n\nHe was [[knighted]]  the same year, and  served as [[Sheriff of County Dublin]]  in 1609. In  1610  he received a substantial grant of land in [[County Armagh]] from the English Crown.  No doubts   seem to have been entertained about his own loyalty to the Crown, except perhaps during the latter part of the  English  Civil War, In  1629 King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] created him [[Viscount FitzWilliam]] in recognition of his family's long record of service to the Crown.<ref>Cokayne  ''Complete Peerage'' 6 volumes. Reissued  2000 Vol. 5, p. 527</ref> It appears that a good deal was expected in return for the title, and Thomas had to make substantial gifts of money  to the King. This put a particular burden on his estates since he was involved in  protracted litigation with his numerous brothers and sisters, due to  his father's breaking of an [[entail]] on the estates, which benefitted Thomas  at the expense of  his siblings. Admittedly Thomas himself had been the beneficiary of a generous Crown grant of land in Armagh.  Like nearly all of his family he inclined to the [[Roman Catholic]]  faith, while adhering in public to the [[Church of Ireland]]; later generations of  Fitzwilliams were quite open in their support for the Catholic  religion.\n\n==Civil war and last years==\nWhen the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]] broke out, FitzWilliam, unlike many of the nobility of the Pale, remained loyal to the Crown, despite strong pressure from his mother's family, the Prestons of Gormanston, to join the [[Irish Confederacy]].<ref>Ball, p.13</ref> He was one of  only three nobles to offer their assistance in the [[Royalist]] defence of Dublin, and a garrison was placed in Merrion Castle. It was betrayed in June 1642 and thereafter FitzWilliam only lived there for short periods. He offered his services\nto the  [[Lord Justices (Ireland)|Lords Justices]], but  despite his long record of loyalty to the Crown he was rebuffed, apparently on account of his known leanings towards the Roman Catholic religion,  and he  took no further part in the fighting.  He spent some time in  England, where the King received him courteously.   He was promised an English [[Earldom]],  but the promise was not kept. He returned to Ireland, only to discover that he had been [[outlawed]]]. In his last years he led an unsettled existence, living  sometimes at Merrion Castle,  sometimes with his eldest son at [[Howth]], and sometimes in [[Louth, County Louth|Louth]]. At times he seems to have been almost destitute, and  he wrote to  [[ James Butler, 1st Duke  of Ormonde]] in 1647 asking for repayment of a [[debt]]. In 1648 he was promised a [[pension]]  of \u00a3100 a year, but it is unclear if he ever received it.<ref>Ball, p.16</ref>\n\nDue perhaps to the confused conditions of the [[ English Civil War]], little seems to be known about the date and place of his death. Even the year has been disputed, but is generally stated to be 1650. He was certainly dead before 1655 when his eldest surviving son Oliver was allowed to inherit a part of the estates, though most of them were not restored until 1663.<ref>Ball, p.18</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1605 he married Margaret Plunkett, daughter of Oliver Plunkett, 4th [[Baron Louth]] and  his wife Frances, who was the daughter of [[Nicholas Bagenal]] and Eleanor Griffith,   and  sister of [[Henry Bagenal]] and of Mabel, Countess of Tyrone.<ref>Cokayne ''Complete Peerage'', p. 527</ref> They had four sons:\n*Richard, who predeceased his father: He married Elizabeth Stanihust but  had no children;\n*[[Oliver FitzWilliam, 1st Earl of Tyrconnell]], he   was married  three times but had no children;\n*Christopher, who lived mainly in England:  he married Jane Brereton of [[Malpas, Cheshire|Malpas]] (whose sister Dorothy was  his brother Oliver's first wife)  and  had one surviving daughter but no son;\n*[[William FitzWilliam, 3rd Viscount FitzWilliam]], ancestor of  all succeeding Viscounts Fitzwilliam. He married Mary Luttrell and had six children.\n\n==Character==\nHis friend [[James Butler, 1st Duke of Ormonde]] described him as a man who was  \"in every way faithful to his allegiance\".<ref>Ball, p.13</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitzwilliam, Thomas Fitzwilliam, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:1581 births]]\n[[Category:1650 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from Mount Merrion]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas FitzWilliam, 1st Viscount Fitzwilliam''' (1581\u20131650) was an Irish nobleman of the Stuart age. He was born to wealth and privilege, and acquired a peerage, but due to his loyalty to the English  Crown he suffered  considerable hardship  during the [[English Civil War]], and died in poverty.\n\n==Background==\nHe was born in [[Dublin]], probably at [[Merrion Castle]], eldest of the five  sons  of Sir Richard FitzWiliam, Constable of [[Wicklow]], and Jane Preston, daughter of Christopher Preston, 4th [[Viscount Gormanston]].<ref>Ball, F. Elrington  ''History of Dublin'' Alexander Thom and Co. Dublin 1902-1920 Vol.2  p.11</ref> The FitzWilliam family are recorded   in Dublin from about 1210, and by the time of Thomas's  birth they  were among the wealthiest and most influential families in [[the Pale]].\n\n==Early career==\nThomas was only fourteen when his father died.  As a young man he spent some time in [[London]] studying law at [[Gray's Inn]].  He  was [[knighted]] in 1605, the year of his marriage.\n\nIn 1608 he narrowly avoided being caught up  in the rebellion of Sir [[Cahir O'Doherty]], having stood [[surety]]  for the good behaviour of O'Doherty, who had married Thomas's  aunt Mary Preston.<ref>Ball, p.12</ref> A messenger arrived at Merrion Castle ordering FitzWilliam to produce the person of O'Doherty; fortunately FitzWilliam was not at home.  \n\nHe was [[knighted]]  the same year, and  served as [[Sheriff of County Dublin]]  in 1609. In  1610  he received a substantial grant of land in [[County Armagh]] from the English Crown.  No doubts   seem to have been entertained about his own loyalty to the Crown, except perhaps during the latter part of the  English  Civil War, In  1629 King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] created him [[Viscount FitzWilliam]] in recognition of his family's long record of service to the Crown.<ref>Cokayne  ''Complete Peerage'' 6 volumes. Reissued  2000 Vol. 5, p. 527</ref> It appears that a good deal was expected in return for the title, and Thomas had to make substantial gifts of money  to the King. This put a particular burden on his estates since he was involved in  protracted litigation with his numerous brothers and sisters, due to  his father's breaking of an [[entail]] on the estates, which benefitted Thomas  at the expense of  his siblings. Admittedly Thomas himself had been the beneficiary of a generous Crown grant of land in Armagh.  Like nearly all of his family he inclined to the [[Roman Catholic]]  faith, while adhering in public to the [[Church of Ireland]]; later generations of  Fitzwilliams were quite open in their support for the Catholic  religion.\n\n==Civil war and last years==\nWhen the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]] broke out, FitzWilliam, unlike many of the nobility of the Pale, remained loyal to the Crown, despite strong pressure from his mother's family, the Prestons of Gormanston, to join the [[Irish Confederacy]].<ref>Ball, p.13</ref> He was one of  only three nobles to offer their assistance in the [[Royalist]] defence of Dublin, and a garrison was placed in Merrion Castle. It was betrayed in June 1642 and thereafter FitzWilliam only lived there for short periods. He offered his services\nto the  [[Lord Justices (Ireland)|Lords Justices]], but  despite his long record of loyalty to the Crown he was rebuffed, apparently on account of his known leanings towards the Roman Catholic religion,  and he  took no further part in the fighting.  He spent some time in  England, where the King received him courteously.   He was promised an English [[Earldom]],  but the promise was not kept. He returned to Ireland, only to discover that he had been [[outlawed]]]. In his last years he led an unsettled existence, living  sometimes at Merrion Castle,  sometimes with his eldest son at [[Howth]], and sometimes in [[Louth, County Louth|Louth]]. At times he seems to have been almost destitute, and  he wrote to  [[ James Butler, 1st Duke  of Ormonde]] in 1647 asking for repayment of a [[debt]]. In 1648 he was promised a [[pension]]  of \u00a3100 a year, but it is unclear if he ever received it.<ref>Ball, p.16</ref>\n\nDue perhaps to the confused conditions of the [[ English Civil War]], little seems to be known about the date and place of his death. Even the year has been disputed, but is generally stated to be 1650. He was certainly dead before 1655 when his eldest surviving son Oliver was allowed to inherit a part of the estates, though most of them were not restored until 1663.<ref>Ball, p.18</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1605 he married Margaret Plunkett, daughter of Oliver Plunkett, 4th [[Baron Louth]] and  his wife Frances, who was the daughter of [[Nicholas Bagenal]] and Eleanor Griffith,   and  sister of [[Henry Bagenal]] and of Mabel, Countess of Tyrone.<ref>Cokayne ''Complete Peerage'', p. 527</ref> They had four sons:\n*Richard, who predeceased his father: He married Elizabeth Stanihust but  had no children;\n*[[Oliver FitzWilliam, 1st Earl of Tyrconnell]], he   was married  three times but had no children;\n*Christopher, who lived mainly in England:  he married Jane Brereton of [[Malpas, Cheshire|Malpas]] (whose sister Dorothy was  his brother Oliver's first wife)  and  had one surviving daughter but no son;\n*[[William FitzWilliam, 3rd Viscount FitzWilliam]], ancestor of  all succeeding Viscounts Fitzwilliam.\n\n==Character==\nHis friend [[James Butler, 1st Duke of Ormonde]] described him as a man who was  \"in every way faithful to his allegiance\".<ref>Ball, p.13</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitzwilliam, Thomas Fitzwilliam, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:1581 births]]\n[[Category:1650 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from Mount Merrion]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Chrisdoyleorwell", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_FitzWilliam,_1st_Viscount_FitzWilliam"}
{"title_page": "2013 AFL Grand Final", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox Australian rules football grand final\n| competition   = AFL\n| year          = 2013\n| image         = 2013 AFL Grand Final logo.png\n| ground_image  = [[File:2013 AFL Grand Final pre-game.JPG|300px]]\n| caption       = View of the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] moments after gates opened for the 2013 AFL Grand Final.\n| home          = [[File:AFL_Hawthorn_Icon.jpg]]<br/>{{AFL Haw}}\n| home_abbr     = HAW\n| home_image    = \n| away          =[[File:AFL Fremantle Icon 2011.png|50px]]<br/>{{AFL Fre}}\n| away_abbr     = FRE\n| away_image    = \n| home_qtr1     = 2.3 (15)\n| home_qtr2     = 5.5 (35)\n| home_qtr3     = 8.8 (56)\n| home_qtr4     = 11.11 (77)\n| away_qtr1     = 0.3 (3)\n| away_qtr2     = 1.6 (12)\n| away_qtr3     = 6.10 (46)\n| away_qtr4     = 8.14 (62)\n| home_score    = 11.11 (77)\n| away_score    = 8.14 (62)\n| date          = {{start date|2013|09|28|df=yes}}, 2:30pm\n| stadium       = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]\n| attendance    = 100,007\n| umpire        = Brett Rosebury, Simon Meredith, Matthew Nicholls\n| coin_toss     = Fremantle\n| kick_end      = City End\n| prematch      = [[Birds of Tokyo]]\n| anthem        = [[Tina Arena]]\n| halftime      = [[Hunters and Collectors]]\n| postmatch     = [[Hunters and Collectors]], [[Birds of Tokyo]]\n| norm_smith    = [[Brian Lake]]\n| jock_mchale   = [[Alastair Clarkson]]\n| network       = [[Seven Network]] \n| announcers    = [[Bruce McAvaney]] (host)<br>[[Hamish McLachlan]] (host)<br>[[Dennis Cometti]] (commentator)<br>[[Wayne Carey]] (expert commentator)<br>[[Cameron Ling]] (expert commentator)<br>[[Leigh Matthews]] (expert commentator)<br>[[Basil Zempilas]] (analyst)<br>[[Brian Taylor (Australian footballer)|Brian Taylor]] (analyst)<br>[[Samantha Lane]] (analyst)<br>[[Matthew Richardson (footballer)|Matthew Richardson]] (boundary rider)<br>[[Tim Watson]] (boundary rider)\n| last          = 2012\n| next          = 2014\n}}\nThe '''2013 AFL Grand Final''' was an [[Australian rules football]] game contested between [[Hawthorn Football Club]] and [[Fremantle Football Club]] at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] on 28 September 2013. It was the 117th annual [[AFL Grand Final|grand final]] of the [[Australian Football League]] (formerly the Victorian Football League),<ref>In 1897 and 1924 there were no grand finals and instead the premier was decided by a finals play-off. In 1948, 1977 and 2010, there were grand final replays after initial draws.</ref> staged to determine the [[List of AFL premiers|premiers]] for the [[2013 AFL season]]. The match, attended by 100,007 spectators, was won by Hawthorn by a margin of 15 points, marking the club's [[List of Australian Football League premiers#AFL premiers (1990-present)|eleventh VFL/AFL premiership victory]]. Hawthorn's [[Brian Lake]] was awarded the [[Norm Smith Medal]] as the best player on the ground.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2013 AFL season}}\n{{further|2013 AFL finals series|2013 Hawthorn Football Club season|2013 Fremantle Football Club season}}\nHawthorn entered the 2013 season having lost the [[2012 AFL Grand Final|2012 Grand Final]] to {{AFL Syd}}, and for most of the season was seen as the favourites for the premiership.<ref>{{cite news | last = Landsberger | first = Sam | title = Hawthorn opens the 2013 premiership market favourite | newspaper = Herald Sun | date = 2012-09-29 | url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/hawthorn-opens-the-2013-premiership-market-favourite/story-e6frf9jf-1226484051889 | accessdate = 2014-04-06 }}</ref> After losing to {{AFL Gee}} in Round 1, Hawthorn compiled a 12-match winning streak, until this streak was ended with another loss to Geelong in Round 15. The club's only other loss came against {{AFL Ric}} in Round 19, and it finished with a record of 19&ndash;3 to win the minor premiership for the second consecutive year. They defeated Sydney in the qualifying final by 54 points and earned a week off. They ended an [[Kennett curse|11-match losing streak against Geelong]] (dating back to [[2008 AFL Grand Final|2008]]) to win by five points in the preliminary final. The match was Hawthorn's third grand final appearance in six years.\n\nFremantle entered the 2013 season having come off a semi-final loss to {{AFL Ade}} in the previous year's finals series. After winning their first two matches of the season by 28 points, the Dockers lost back-to-back matches against {{AFL Ess}} and {{AFL Haw}} to be 2&ndash;2 after Round 4 &ndash; this was the only time they lost consecutive matches during the season. Fremantle recorded its largest ever victory when they defeated {{AFL GWS}} in Round 20, then, with a finals berth guaranteed, Ross Lyon rested half of his regular side ahead of its final regular season match against {{AFL Stk}}; the result was a 71-point defeat, which marked the worst defeat in Lyon's coaching career. The team finished third at the end of the home-and-away season, and compiled a club-best record of 16\u20135\u20131. They unexpectedly defeated {{AFL Gee}} in [[Kardinia Park|Geelong]] by 15 points in the first week of the finals (an upset that is still regarded by many as the greatest victory in the team's history), which earnt them a week off and a home preliminary final. Fremantle  defeated the reigning premiers, Sydney, by 25 points in the preliminary final. The match was Fremantle's first grand final in its history.\n\nThe two teams met once during the regular season, in Round 4 at [[York Park|Aurora Stadium]]; Hawthorn won by 42 points.\n\n==Media Coverage==\nThe match was televised by the [[Seven Network]]. The primary match commentary was provided by [[Bruce McAvaney]] and [[Dennis Cometti]].\n\n==Pre-match entertainment==\nTwo Australian bands, [[Birds of Tokyo]] and [[Hunters & Collectors]] performed before the game and at half time, respectively.  The [[Australian national anthem]] was sung by [[Tina Arena]].<ref name=\"Ent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/afl/afl-news/afl-grand-final-2013-entertainment-headlined-by-local-acts-20130902-2sztb.html|title=AFL grand final 2013 entertainment headlined by local acts|date=2 September 2013|first=Patrick |last=Bartley|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]}}</ref>\n\n==Match summary==\n\n===First quarter===\nFremantle won the coin toss and chose to kick towards the City End of the MCG in the first quarter. However, it was Hawthorn who got off to a good start, with [[Jack Gunston]] kicking the first goal before [[Lance Franklin]] kicked the Hawks' second after [[Luke McPharlin]] gave away a [[50-metre penalty]] for stepping over the mark. Hawthorn then had a few chances to extend their margin, however a rushed behind, combined with missed opportunities by [[Shaun Burgoyne]] and [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Isaac Smith]], had little influence on the scoreboard. Meanwhile, Fremantle were held goalless in the opening quarter with [[Hayden Ballantyne]] and [[Nick Suban]] missing relatively easy shots on goal whilst [[Nathan Fyfe]] missed two shots completely with both going out on the full. At quarter time, the Hawks had a 12 point lead.\n\n===Second quarter===\nHawthorn started off the quarter strongly, taking a stranglehold of the game against the Dockers. [[Jack Gunston]] kicked his second goal on the run from just inside 50 before [[Cyril Rioli]] through his manic forward pressure, got himself on the board after catching [[Lee Spurr]] for holding the ball, taking the Hawks to a massive 24 point lead. Finally at the 12 minute mark, [[Tendai Mzungu]] kicked the Dockers' first goal, before [[Ryan Crowley]] kicked yet another behind for Fremantle. This was quickly followed by [[Jack Gunston]] slotting his third goal after outpositioning Fremantle's [[Zac Dawson]]. The two teams then exchanged behinds with Rioli and [[Brad Sewell]] for Hawthorn and [[Matthew Pavlich]] and [[Nat Fyfe]] for Fremantle all registering minor scores as Hawthorn enjoyed a 23 point lead at half time. Fremantle\u2019s first half score of 1.6 (12) was the lowest in a grand final since [[1960 VFL Grand Final|1960]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-09-28/afl-grand-final-2013-hawthorn-fremantle-live-blog/4985912?section=sport|title= AFL grand final 2013: Hawthorn v Fremantle as it happened|date=28 September 2013|work=ABC.net|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Third quarter===\nAfter failing to capitalise on their chances in the first half, Fremantle began a comeback in the third quarter. Within a minute, Fremantle captain [[Matthew Pavlich]] kicked his first goal, however this was later cancelled out by a goal to [[Jarryd Roughead]]. This was followed by 3 goals in succession to Femantle with goals to Pavlich, [[Michael Walters]], a massive 55 metre set shot bomb from [[Chris Mayne]] and a behind from [[David Mundy]] to take the Dockers within 3 points of the Hawks. The Hawks tried to respond with a flurry of their own, however missed opportunities to Roughead and [[Cyril Rioli]] only made little difference to the margin. Roughead later managed to kick his second goal after he was pushed in the back, but Fremantle replied as behinds to [[Stephen Hill (Australian footballer)|Stephen Hill]] and [[Michael Barlow]] and Walters kicking his second goal once again allowed them to close within 3 points. Moments later, Hawthorn replied again as [[Jack Gunston]] kicked his fourth goal. Gunston then has another opportunity through a set shot but misses it to the right as the Hawks entered the three-quarter-time break ten points ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/28/hawthorn-fremantle-afl-grand-final-live|title= Hawthorn v Fremantle: AFL grand final \u2013 as it happened|date=28 September 2013|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Final quarter===\nAs much as the majority of the 3rd quarter was dominated by Fremantle, the first half of the fourth quarter was dominated by the Hawks as they booted 3 unanswered goals to take themselves to a match winning 31 point lead. [[Jarryd Roughead]] missed a shot with his snap going wide before [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Isaac Smith]] slotted a massive goal from a set shot 55 metres out in similar fashion to [[Chris Mayne]]'s goal in the third quarter. Additional goals to [[Luke Breust]] and [[Bradley Hill (footballer)|Bradley Hill]] and behinds from Roughead and [[Lance Franklin]] put the result beyond doubt, stretching their lead to 31 points. During Hawthorn\u2019s period of dominance, [[Brian Lake]], a recently recruited defender from the [[Western Bulldogs]], was instrumental in shutting down Fremantle\u2019s attacks, taking two critical contested marks from opposing kicks, to help his team to victory. Fremantle tried hard to make a final comeback with two late goals to [[Danyle Pearce]] and [[Matthew Pavlich]] to give the Dockers some hope. However, Fremantle\u2019s inability on the day to convert their opportunities was summed up as [[Hayden Ballantyne]] and Pavlich missed two crucial shots on goal, whereas another opportunity was rushed through for a behind. Fremantle then had one last opportunity to get themselves back into the game. With 90 seconds remaining, [[Ryan Crowley]] had a running shot on goal in an open paddock which would\u2019ve bought the Dockers to within 2 kicks of the Hawks, however, he was run down and tackled by [[Ben Stratton]] with the ensuing kick missing to the right. Hawthorn were then able to hold on to win the grand final by 15 points, avenging their grand final loss the previous year.<ref name=\"GF\">[http://www.theroar.com.au/2013/09/29/what-we-learnt-from-the-2013-afl-grand-final/ What we learnt from the 2013 AFL Grand Final], ''The Roar'', 29 September 2013</ref>\n\n===Overall report===\n{{wide image|MCG Grand Final panorama.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|A panoramic view of the Melbourne Cricket Ground during the 2013 Grand Final.}}\nHawthorn led the match from start to finish, but were outplayed for significant periods. It is the only grand final which Champion Data have assessed as having been won by the poorer side on the day, as Fremantle were left to rue their opportunities they were unable to convert.<ref>http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/champion-data-fremantle-should-have-beaten-hawthorn-by-six-points-in-the-2013-grand-final/news-story/00d982ed553da77d96464b78af79ed82</ref>\n\n2013 remains the only time the Fremantle Dockers have appeared in an AFL Grand Final since joining the league in 1995 (and hence the closest they have come to an AFL Premiership).  Two years later in [[2015 AFL season|2015]], Fremantle won the [[minor premiership]] for finishing on top of the AFL ladder at the end of the home & away season, but they failed to convert that achievement into another grand final appearance, losing to Hawthorn in the Preliminary Final.<ref name=\"GF\"/>\n\n===Norm Smith Medal===\n[[Brian Lake]] took ten marks of which seven were intercept marks to repel the Dockers attack. He took two crucial marks in the final quarter which sealed his Norm Smith Medal win. Lake finished with 12 votes, just edging out teammate [[Jack Gunston]] with 11 votes who was also crucial on the day with his straight kicking, booting 4 goals. [[David Mundy]] polled 4 votes, while [[Luke Hodge]] and [[Nat Fyfe]] polled 2 and 1 votes respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-09-28/live-2013-grand-final|title= 2013 Grand Final as it happened|date=28 September 2013|work=AFL.com|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref> He subsequently accepted a four match suspension for deliberately elbowing opponent Michael Walters in the jaw during the third quarter, making him the first Norm Smith Medalist to have committed a reportable offence during a match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-09-30/hawk-heroes-handed-bans|title=Lake, Rioli banned, Suban to Tribunal - AFL.com.au|author=|date=|website=afl.com.au}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Australian rules football kit\n| pattern_b       = _brown_stripes_copia\n| pattern_sh      =  \n| pattern_so      = _hoops_gold\n| body          = FBBF15\n| shorts         = 823F00\n| socks          = 823F00\n | title      = Hawthorn  \n}}\n|{{Australian rules football kit\n | pattern_b  = _3purplev\n | pattern_sh =  _sides_on_white\n | pattern_so =  _3whitehoops\n | body       = ffffff\n | shorts     = 2A1A54 \n | socks      = 2A1A54\n | title      = Fremantle\n}}\n|}\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Aussie rules team | title =     {{font color|#4D2004|Hawthorn|link=Hawthorn Football Club}} | color = #FBBF15      \n| backpocket1 = 24 [[Ben Stratton]]\n| fullback = 17 [[Brian Lake]]\n| backpocket2 = 18 [[Brent Guerra]]\n| halfbackflank1 = 9 [[Shaun Burgoyne]]\n| centrehalfback = 6 [[Josh Gibson (footballer)|Josh Gibson]]\n| halfbackflank2 = 14 [[Grant Birchall]]\n| wing1 = 16 [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Isaac Smith]]\n| centre = 5 [[Sam Mitchell (footballer)|Sam Mitchell]]\n| wing2 = 3 [[Jordan Lewis]]\n| halfforwardflank1 = 22 [[Luke Breust]]\n| centrehalfforward = 23 [[Lance Franklin]]\n| halfforwardflank2 = 33 [[Cyril Rioli]]\n| forwardpocket1 = 28 [[Paul Puopolo]]\n| fullforward = 2 [[Jarryd Roughead]]\n| forwardpocket2 = 20 [[David Hale (footballer)|David Hale]]\n| ruck = 39 [[Max Bailey]]\n| ruckrover = 12 [[Brad Sewell]]\n| rover = 15 [[Luke Hodge]] ([[Captain (Australian rules football)|c]])\n| interchange1 = 26 [[Liam Shiels]]\n| interchange2 = 19 [[Jack Gunston]]\n| interchange3 = 10 [[Bradley Hill (footballer)|Bradley Hill]]\n| interchange4 = 32 [[Jonathan Simpkin]] (sub)\n| interchange5 = \n| interchange6 = \n| coach = [[Alastair Clarkson]]\n}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Aussie rules team | title =     {{font color|#FFFFFF|Fremantle|link=Fremantle Football Club}} | color = #2A1A54     \n| backpocket1 = 41 [[Paul Duffield]]\n| fullback = 3 [[Zac Dawson]]\n| backpocket2 = 37 [[Michael Johnson (Australian rules footballer)|Michael Johnson]]\n| halfbackflank1 = 6 [[Danyle Pearce]]\n| centrehalfback = 18 [[Luke McPharlin]]\n| halfbackflank2 = 34 [[Lee Spurr]]\n| wing1 = 13 [[Tendai Mzungu]]\n| centre = 15 [[Ryan Crowley]]\n| wing2 = 16 [[David Mundy]]\n| halfforwardflank1 = 7 [[Nathan Fyfe]]\n| centrehalfforward = 23 [[Chris Mayne]]\n| halfforwardflank2 = 33 [[Cameron Sutcliffe]]\n| forwardpocket1 = 10 [[Michael Walters]]\n| fullforward = 29 [[Matthew Pavlich]] ([[Captain (Australian rules football)|c]])\n| forwardpocket2 = 30 [[Zac Clarke]]\n| ruck = 31 [[Aaron Sandilands]]\n| ruckrover = 9 [[Matt de Boer]]\n| rover = 32 [[Stephen Hill (Australian footballer)|Stephen Hill]]\n| interchange1 = 1 [[Hayden Ballantyne]]\n| interchange2 = 8 [[Nick Suban]]\n| interchange3 = 21 [[Michael Barlow]]\n| interchange4 = 27 [[Lachie Neale]] (sub)\n| interchange5 = \n| interchange6 = \n| coach = [[Ross Lyon]]\n}}\n|}\n\n;Umpires\nThe umpiring panel for the grand final comprised nine match day umpires and three emergencies. Among the umpires were four grand final debutants: field umpire [[Mathew Nicholls]], boundary umpires Michael Marantelli and Michael Saunders, and goal umpire Adam Wojcik.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aflua.com.au/afl-announces-grand-final-umpires/|title=AFL announces Grand Final umpires|date=24 September 2013|author=Julia Gauci|accessdate=26 September 2013|publisher=Australian Football League Umpires Association}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ 2013 AFL Grand Final umpires\n! Position !! Umpire 1 !! Umpire 2 !! Umpire 3 !! Umpire 4 !! rowspan=\"4\" |  !! Emergency\n|-\n| {{rh}} | [[Umpire (Australian rules football)|Field]]:\n| 8 [[Brett Rosebury]] (6)\n| 15 [[Mathew Nicholls]] (1)\n| 21 [[Simon Meredith (umpire)|Simon Meredith]] (2)\n| \n| 9 [[Matt Stevic]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\"| '''[[Umpire (Australian rules football)|Boundary]]:\n| Nathan Doig (2)\n| Robert Haala (2)\n| Michael Marantelli (1)\n| Michael Saunders (1)\n| Matthew Tomkins\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\"| '''[[Umpire (Australian rules football)|Goal]]:\n| Luke Walker (5)\n| Adam Wojcik (1)\n|\n| \n| Chris Appleton\n|}\n''Numbers in brackets represent the number of grand finals umpired; this number includes 2013 and does not include times selected as an emergency umpire.''\n\n==Scorecard==\n\n{{AFLGameDetailed\n|title = Grand Final\n|date = Saturday, 28 September (2:30&nbsp;pm)\n|home team = {{AFL Haw}}\n|home Q1 = 2.3 (15)\n|home Q2 = 5.5 (35)\n|home Q3 = 8.8 (56)\n|home final = 11.11 (77)\n|home goals= [[Jack Gunston|Gunston]] 4<br/> [[Jarryd Roughead|Roughead]] 2<br/> [[Lance Franklin|Franklin]], [[Cyril Rioli|Rioli]], [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Smith]], [[Luke Breust|Breust]], [[Bradley Hill (footballer)|Hill]] 1\n|home best = &nbsp; [[Brian Lake|Lake]], [[Jack Gunston|Gunston]], [[Jordan Lewis|Lewis]], [[Cyril Rioli|Rioli]], [[Luke Hodge|Hodge]], [[Grant Birchall|Birchall]]\n|home injuries = &nbsp; Nil\n|home reports = [[Brian Lake|Lake]] - Striking; [[Cyril Rioli|Rioli]] - Rough conduct\n|winner = H\n|away team = {{AFL Fre}}\n|away Q1 = 0.3 (3)\n|away Q2 = 1.6 (12)\n|away Q3 = 6.10 (46)\n|away final = 8.14 (62)\n|away goals= 3 [[Matthew Pavlich|Pavlich]]<br/>2 [[Michael Walters|Walters]]<br/>1 [[Tendai Mzungu|Mzungu]], [[Chris Mayne|Mayne]], [[Danyle Pearce|Pearce]]\n|away best= &nbsp; [[David Mundy|Mundy]], [[Nathan Fyfe|Fyfe]], [[Ryan Crowley|Crowley]], [[Michael Johnson (footballer born 1988)|Johnson]], [[Michael Barlow|Barlow]]\n|away injuries = &nbsp; Nil\n|away reports = [[Nick Suban|Suban]] - Misconduct\n|venue =  <abbr title=\"15\u00b0 A few showers clearing. Windy.\">[[File:Soare cu nori.png|16px]]</abbr> [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|crowd = 100,007\n|report = [http://www.afl.com.au/match-centre/2013/27/haw-v-fre Report]\n|umpires = [[Brett Rosebury]], [[Mathew Nicholls]], [[Simon Meredith (umpire)|Simon Meredith]]\n|BOG award = [[Norm Smith Medal]]\n|BOG winner = [[Brian Lake]]\n|broadcast = [[Seven Network]]\n|anthem = [[Tina Arena]]\n}}\n\n==Tribunal==\nThe following Monday, the [[AFL Tribunal|Match Review Panel]] adjudicated on two offences incurred by Hawthorn's [[Brian Lake]] and [[Cyril Rioli]], both of which carried the double points loading of due to being incurred during a grand final.  The third offence of misconduct against Fremantle's [[Nick Suban]] was referred directly to the Tribunal for assessment, which determined the incident was improper but not grievous. Suban pleaded guilty to the incident and apologized for what he felt to be an accident.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Player\n! Charge\n! Penalty\n|-\n|[[Nick Suban]], [[Fremantle Football Club|Fremantle]]\n|Unreasonable and unnecessary contact to the face of [[Sam Mitchell (footballer)|Sam Mitchell]], [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]], in the 1st Quarter.<ref name=\"gf-reports\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-09-30/hawk-heroes-handed-bans|title=Hawk heroes handed bans|date=30 September 2013|author=David Schout|publisher=Australian Football League}}</ref>\n|Referred to the Tribunal. Suban pleaded guilty; suspended one match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-10-01/suban-to-miss-one-afl-game/4992272?section=sport|title=Fremantle's Nick Suban to miss one AFL game after grand final gouge on Hawthorn's Sam Mitchell|date=1 October 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cyril Rioli]], [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]\n|Rough conduct (chicken-wing tackle) against [[Michael Barlow]], [[Fremantle Football Club|Fremantle]], in the 3rd Quarter.<ref name=\"gf-reports\" />\n|Pled guilty; suspended one match.<ref name=\"gf-pleas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-10-02/lake-rioli-to-miss-2014-start|title=Lake, Rioli to miss start of next season|date=2 October 2013|author=Mark Macgugan|publisher=Australian Football League}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Brian Lake]], [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]\n|Striking [[Michael Walters]], [[Fremantle Football Club|Fremantle]], in the 3rd Quarter.<ref name=\"gf-reports\" />\n|Pled guilty; suspended three matches.<ref name=\"gf-pleas\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2013 NAB Cup]]\n* [[2013 AFL season]]\n* [[2013 AFL finals series]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2013 Hawthorn premiership players}}\n{{Hawthorn Football Club}}\n{{Fremantle Football Club}}\n{{2013 AFL season}}\n{{Australian Football League}}\n\n[[Category:VFL/AFL Grand Finals]]\n[[Category:2013 Australian Football League season|Grand Final]]\n[[Category:Hawthorn Football Club]]\n[[Category:Fremantle Football Club]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox Australian rules football grand final\n| competition   = AFL\n| year          = 2013\n| image         = 2013 AFL Grand Final logo.png\n| ground_image  = [[File:2013 AFL Grand Final pre-game.JPG|300px]]\n| caption       = View of the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] moments after gates opened for the 2013 AFL Grand Final.\n| home          = [[File:AFL_Hawthorn_Icon.jpg]]<br/>{{AFL Haw}}\n| home_abbr     = HAW\n| home_image    = \n| away          =[[File:AFL Fremantle Icon 2011.png|50px]]<br/>{{AFL Fre}}\n| away_abbr     = FRE\n| away_image    = \n| home_qtr1     = 2.3 (15)\n| home_qtr2     = 5.5 (35)\n| home_qtr3     = 8.8 (56)\n| home_qtr4     = 11.11 (77)\n| away_qtr1     = 0.3 (3)\n| away_qtr2     = 1.6 (12)\n| away_qtr3     = 6.10 (46)\n| away_qtr4     = 8.14 (62)\n| home_score    = 11.11 (77)\n| away_score    = 8.14 (62)\n| date          = {{start date|2013|09|28|df=yes}}, 2:30pm\n| stadium       = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]\n| attendance    = 100,007\n| umpire        = Brett Rosebury, Simon Meredith, Matthew Nicholls\n| coin_toss     = Fremantle\n| kick_end      = City End\n| prematch      = [[Birds of Tokyo]]\n| anthem        = [[Tina Arena]]\n| halftime      = [[Hunters and Collectors]]\n| postmatch     = [[Hunters and Collectors]], [[Birds of Tokyo]]\n| norm_smith    = [[Brian Lake]]\n| jock_mchale   = [[Alastair Clarkson]]\n| network       = [[Seven Network]] \n| announcers    = [[Bruce McAvaney]] (host)<br>[[Hamish McLachlan]] (host)<br>[[Dennis Cometti]] (commentator)<br>[[Wayne Carey]] (expert commentator)<br>[[Cameron Ling]] (expert commentator)<br>[[Leigh Matthews]] (expert commentator)<br>[[Basil Zempilas]] (analyst)<br>[[Brian Taylor (Australian footballer)|Brian Taylor]] (analyst)<br>[[Samantha Lane]] (analyst)<br>[[Matthew Richardson (footballer)|Matthew Richardson]] (boundary rider)<br>[[Tim Watson]] (boundary rider)\n| last          = 2012\n| next          = 2014\n}}\nThe '''2013 AFL Grand Final''' was an [[Australian rules football]] game contested between [[Hawthorn Football Club]] and [[Fremantle Football Club]] at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] on 28 September 2013. It was the 117th annual [[AFL Grand Final|grand final]] of the [[Australian Football League]] (formerly the Victorian Football League),<ref>In 1897 and 1924 there were no grand finals and instead the premier was decided by a finals play-off. In 1948, 1977 and 2010, there were grand final replays after initial draws.</ref> staged to determine the [[List of AFL premiers|premiers]] for the [[2013 AFL season]]. The match, attended by 100,007 spectators, was won by Hawthorn by a margin of 15 points, marking the club's [[List of Australian Football League premiers#AFL premiers (1990-present)|eleventh VFL/AFL premiership victory]]. Hawthorn's [[Brian Lake]] was awarded the [[Norm Smith Medal]] as the best player on the ground.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2013 AFL season}}\n{{further|2013 AFL finals series|2013 Hawthorn Football Club season|2013 Fremantle Football Club season}}\nHawthorn entered the 2013 season having lost the [[2012 AFL Grand Final|2012 Grand Final]] to {{AFL Syd}}, and for most of the season was seen as the favourites for the premiership.<ref>{{cite news | last = Landsberger | first = Sam | title = Hawthorn opens the 2013 premiership market favourite | newspaper = Herald Sun | date = 2012-09-29 | url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/hawthorn-opens-the-2013-premiership-market-favourite/story-e6frf9jf-1226484051889 | accessdate = 2014-04-06 }}</ref> After losing to {{AFL Gee}} in Round 1, Hawthorn compiled a 12-match winning streak, until this streak was ended with another loss to Geelong in Round 15. The club's only other loss came against {{AFL Ric}} in Round 19, and it finished with a record of 19&ndash;3 to win the minor premiership for the second consecutive year. They defeated Sydney in the qualifying final by 54 points and earned a week off. They ended an [[Kennett curse|11-match losing streak against Geelong]] (dating back to [[2008 AFL Grand Final|2008]]) to win by five points in the preliminary final. The match was Hawthorn's third grand final appearance in six years.\n\nFremantle entered the 2013 season having come off a semi-final loss to {{AFL Ade}} in the previous year's finals series. After winning their first two matches of the season by 28 points, the Dockers lost back-to-back matches against {{AFL Ess}} and {{AFL Haw}} to be 2&ndash;2 after Round 4 &ndash; this was the only time they lost consecutive matches during the season. Fremantle recorded its largest ever victory when they defeated {{AFL GWS}} in Round 20, then, with a finals berth guaranteed, Ross Lyon rested half of his regular side ahead of its final regular season match against {{AFL Stk}}; the result was a 71-point defeat, which marked the worst defeat in Lyon's coaching career. The team finished third at the end of the home-and-away season, and compiled a club-best record of 16\u20135\u20131. They unexpectedly defeated {{AFL Gee}} in [[Kardinia Park|Geelong]] by 15 points in the first week of the finals (an upset that is still regarded by many as the greatest victory in the teams history), which earnt them a week off and a home preliminary final. Fremantle  defeated the reigning premiers, Sydney, by 25 points in the preliminary final. The match was Fremantle's first grand final in its history.\n\nThe two teams met once during the regular season, in Round 4 at [[York Park|Aurora Stadium]]; Hawthorn won by 42 points.\n\n==Media Coverage==\nThe match was televised by the [[Seven Network]]. The primary match commentary was provided by [[Bruce McAvaney]] and [[Dennis Cometti]].\n\n==Pre-match entertainment==\nTwo Australian bands, [[Birds of Tokyo]] and [[Hunters & Collectors]] performed before the game and at half time, respectively.  The [[Australian national anthem]] was sung by [[Tina Arena]].<ref name=\"Ent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/afl/afl-news/afl-grand-final-2013-entertainment-headlined-by-local-acts-20130902-2sztb.html|title=AFL grand final 2013 entertainment headlined by local acts|date=2 September 2013|first=Patrick |last=Bartley|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]}}</ref>\n\n==Match summary==\n\n===First quarter===\nFremantle won the coin toss and chose to kick towards the City End of the MCG in the first quarter. However, it was Hawthorn who got off to a good start, with [[Jack Gunston]] kicking the first goal before [[Lance Franklin]] kicked the Hawks' second after [[Luke McPharlin]] gave away a [[50-metre penalty]] for stepping over the mark. Hawthorn then had a few chances to extend their margin, however a rushed behind, combined with missed opportunities by [[Shaun Burgoyne]] and [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Isaac Smith]], had little influence on the scoreboard. Meanwhile, Fremantle were held goalless in the opening quarter with [[Hayden Ballantyne]] and [[Nick Suban]] missing relatively easy shots on goal whilst [[Nathan Fyfe]] missed two shots completely with both going out on the full. At quarter time, the Hawks had a 12 point lead.\n\n===Second quarter===\nHawthorn started off the quarter strongly, taking a stranglehold of the game against the Dockers. [[Jack Gunston]] kicked his second goal on the run from just inside 50 before [[Cyril Rioli]] through his manic forward pressure, got himself on the board after catching [[Lee Spurr]] for holding the ball, taking the Hawks to a massive 24 point lead. Finally at the 12 minute mark, [[Tendai Mzungu]] kicked the Dockers' first goal, before [[Ryan Crowley]] kicked yet another behind for Fremantle. This was quickly followed by [[Jack Gunston]] slotting his third goal after outpositioning Fremantle's [[Zac Dawson]]. The two teams then exchanged behinds with Rioli and [[Brad Sewell]] for Hawthorn and [[Matthew Pavlich]] and [[Nat Fyfe]] for Fremantle all registering minor scores as Hawthorn enjoyed a 23 point lead at half time. Fremantle\u2019s first half score of 1.6 (12) was the lowest in a grand final since [[1960 VFL Grand Final|1960]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-09-28/afl-grand-final-2013-hawthorn-fremantle-live-blog/4985912?section=sport|title= AFL grand final 2013: Hawthorn v Fremantle as it happened|date=28 September 2013|work=ABC.net|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Third quarter===\nAfter failing to capitalise on their chances in the first half, Fremantle began a comeback in the third quarter. Within a minute, Fremantle captain [[Matthew Pavlich]] kicked his first goal, however this was later cancelled out by a goal to [[Jarryd Roughead]]. This was followed by 3 goals in succession to Femantle with goals to Pavlich, [[Michael Walters]], a massive 55 metre set shot bomb from [[Chris Mayne]] and a behind from [[David Mundy]] to take the Dockers within 3 points of the Hawks. The Hawks tried to respond with a flurry of their own, however missed opportunities to Roughead and [[Cyril Rioli]] only made little difference to the margin. Roughead later managed to kick his second goal after he was pushed in the back, but Fremantle replied as behinds to [[Stephen Hill (Australian footballer)|Stephen Hill]] and [[Michael Barlow]] and Walters kicking his second goal once again allowed them to close within 3 points. Moments later, Hawthorn replied again as [[Jack Gunston]] kicked his fourth goal. Gunston then has another opportunity through a set shot but misses it to the right as the Hawks entered the three-quarter-time break ten points ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/28/hawthorn-fremantle-afl-grand-final-live|title= Hawthorn v Fremantle: AFL grand final \u2013 as it happened|date=28 September 2013|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Final quarter===\nAs much as the majority of the 3rd quarter was dominated by Fremantle, the first half of the fourth quarter was dominated by the Hawks as they booted 3 unanswered goals to take themselves to a match winning 31 point lead. [[Jarryd Roughead]] missed a shot with his snap going wide before [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Isaac Smith]] slotted a massive goal from a set shot 55 metres out in similar fashion to [[Chris Mayne]]\u2019s goal in the third quarter. Additional goals to [[Luke Breust]] and [[Bradley Hill (footballer)|Bradley Hill]] and behinds from Roughead and [[Lance Franklin]] put the result beyond doubt, stretching their lead to 31 points. During Hawthorn\u2019s period of dominance, [[Brian Lake]], a recently recruited defender from the [[Western Bulldogs]], was instrumental in shutting down Fremantle\u2019s attacks, taking two critical contested marks from opposing kicks, to help his team to victory. Fremantle tried hard to make a final comeback with two late goals to [[Danyle Pearce]] and [[Matthew Pavlich]] to give the Dockers some hope. However, Fremantle\u2019s inability on the day to convert their opportunities was summed up as [[Hayden Ballantyne]] and Pavlich missed two crucial shots on goal, whereas another opportunity was rushed through for a behind. Fremantle then had one last opportunity to get themselves back into the game. With 90 seconds remaining, [[Ryan Crowley]] had a running shot on goal in an open paddock which would\u2019ve bought the Dockers to within 2 kicks of the Hawks, however, he was run down and tackled by [[Ben Stratton]] with the ensuing kick missing to the right. Hawthorn were then able to hold on to win the grand final by 15 points, avenging their grand final loss the previous year.<ref name=\"GF\">[http://www.theroar.com.au/2013/09/29/what-we-learnt-from-the-2013-afl-grand-final/ What we learnt from the 2013 AFL Grand Final], ''The Roar'', 29 September 2013</ref>\n\n===Overall report===\n{{wide image|MCG Grand Final panorama.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|A panoramic view of the Melbourne Cricket Ground during the 2013 Grand Final.}}\nHawthorn led the match from start to finish, but were outplayed for significant periods. It is the only grand final which Champion Data have assessed as having been won by the poorer side on the day, as Fremantle were left to rue their opportunities they were unable to convert.<ref>http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/champion-data-fremantle-should-have-beaten-hawthorn-by-six-points-in-the-2013-grand-final/news-story/00d982ed553da77d96464b78af79ed82</ref>\n\n2013 remains the only time the Fremantle Dockers have appeared in an AFL Grand Final since joining the league in 1995 (and hence the closest they have come to an AFL Premiership).  Two years later in [[2015 AFL season|2015]], Fremantle won the [[minor premiership]] for finishing on top of the AFL ladder at the end of the home & away season, but they failed to convert that achievement into another grand final appearance, losing to Hawthorn in the Preliminary Final.<ref name=\"GF\"/>\n\n===Norm Smith Medal===\n[[Brian Lake]] took ten marks of which seven were intercept marks to repel the Dockers attack. He took two crucial marks in the final quarter which sealed his Norm Smith Medal win. Lake finished with 12 votes, just edging out teammate [[Jack Gunston]] with 11 votes who was also crucial on the day with his straight kicking, booting 4 goals. [[David Mundy]] polled 4 votes, while [[Luke Hodge]] and [[Nat Fyfe]] polled 2 and 1 votes respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-09-28/live-2013-grand-final|title= 2013 Grand Final as it happened|date=28 September 2013|work=AFL.com|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref> He subsequently accepted a four match suspension for deliberately elbowing opponent Michael Walters in the jaw during the third quarter, making him the first Norm Smith Medalist to have committed a reportable offence during a match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-09-30/hawk-heroes-handed-bans|title=Lake, Rioli banned, Suban to Tribunal - AFL.com.au|author=|date=|website=afl.com.au}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Australian rules football kit\n| pattern_b       = _brown_stripes_copia\n| pattern_sh      =  \n| pattern_so      = _hoops_gold\n| body          = FBBF15\n| shorts         = 823F00\n| socks          = 823F00\n | title      = Hawthorn  \n}}\n|{{Australian rules football kit\n | pattern_b  = _3purplev\n | pattern_sh =  _sides_on_white\n | pattern_so =  _3whitehoops\n | body       = ffffff\n | shorts     = 2A1A54 \n | socks      = 2A1A54\n | title      = Fremantle\n}}\n|}\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Aussie rules team | title =     {{font color|#4D2004|Hawthorn|link=Hawthorn Football Club}} | color = #FBBF15      \n| backpocket1 = 24 [[Ben Stratton]]\n| fullback = 17 [[Brian Lake]]\n| backpocket2 = 18 [[Brent Guerra]]\n| halfbackflank1 = 9 [[Shaun Burgoyne]]\n| centrehalfback = 6 [[Josh Gibson (footballer)|Josh Gibson]]\n| halfbackflank2 = 14 [[Grant Birchall]]\n| wing1 = 16 [[Isaac Smith (footballer)|Isaac Smith]]\n| centre = 5 [[Sam Mitchell (footballer)|Sam Mitchell]]\n| wing2 = 3 [[Jordan Lewis]]\n| halfforwardflank1 = 22 [[Luke Breust]]\n| centrehalfforward = 23 [[Lance Franklin]]\n| halfforwardflank2 = 33 [[Cyril Rioli]]\n| forwardpocket1 = 28 [[Paul Puopolo]]\n| fullforward = 2 [[Jarryd Roughead]]\n| forwardpocket2 = 20 [[David Hale (footballer)|David Hale]]\n| ruck = 39 [[Max Bailey]]\n| 